  "viewBox": { "width": 800, "height": 400 },
  "theory": "Paging is a memory management scheme that eliminates the need for contiguous allocation of physical memory. The process's logical address space can be non-contiguous, and the physical memory is divided into fixed-size blocks called frames. The logical memory is divided into blocks of the same size called pages.\n\nEvery address generated by the CPU is divided into two parts:\n1. Page Number (p): Used as an index into a page table. The page table contains the base address of each page in physical memory (the frame number).\n2. Page Offset (d): Combined with the base address to define the physical memory address that is sent to the memory unit. The page offset remains unchanged during translation because the page size is equal to the frame size.\n\nWhen the CPU registers a logical address, the hardware extracts the page number 'p' and uses it to look up the corresponding frame number 'f' in the Page Table. Once 'f' is found, the physical address is constructed as the combination of 'f' and 'd'. This physical address is then used to locate the target frame and the exact data byte in the Physical Memory.",
  "keyPoints": [
    "Logical Address is divided into Page Number (p) and Page Offset (d).",
    "Page Table maps the Page Number (p) to the Physical Frame Number (f).",
    "Page Offset (d) is copied directly to the Physical Address without any translation.",
    "Physical Address consists of the Frame Number (f) and Page Offset (d).",
    "Paging avoids external fragmentation and allows sharing of common code pages."
  ],
  "examTip": "In examinations, remember to clearly show that the page offset 'd' goes directly to the physical address without modification, while 'p' acts as an index to lookup 'f' in the page table. The relation is: Physical Address = (f * page_size) + d.",
  "useCases": [
    "Modern virtual memory systems implementing paging in Windows, Linux, and macOS.",
    "Hardware-level address translation handled by the Memory Management Unit (MMU).",
    "Enabling processes to run even when their virtual memory space is larger than physical RAM."
  ],
